{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522226"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:42:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:42:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13814"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13814"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.15,0.01,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6431"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49284"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6431"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34499"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"1263"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12702"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13631"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49284"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with complaints of excessive breast growth over the past 12 months. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes, congestive heart failure, and polymyalgia rheumatica. His medications include prednisolone, bisoprolol, sacubitril/valsartan, spironolactone, metformin, and linagliptin. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears overweight with a body mass index of 28 kg/m2. His vital signs are within normal limits. There is prominent symmetrical gynaecomastia with no palpable focal masses. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely contributing to the patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spironolactone","Prednisolone","Sacubitril","Linagliptin","Metformin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E is the medication most likely contributing to this patient\u0027s gynaecomastia. Spironolactone is an aldosterone antagonist commonly used in heart failure treatment. It has anti-androgenic effects and can cause gynaecomastia, particularly in older men. The mechanism involves both androgen receptor blockade and increased estrogen production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E, while a glucocorticoid that can affect hormone balance, is less commonly associated with gynaecomastia compared to spironolactone. However, long-term use of high-dose glucocorticoids can potentially contribute to breast tissue growth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESacubitril\u003C/strong\u003E, an neprilysin inhibitor used in combination with valsartan for heart failure, has not been significantly associated with gynaecomastia. Its effects are primarily on the cardiovascular and renal systems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELinagliptin\u003C/strong\u003E, a dipeptidyl peptidase-4 (DPP-4) inhibitor used for diabetes management, has not been linked to gynaecomastia. Its primary action is on blood glucose control through incretin hormone regulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin\u003C/strong\u003E, a biguanide antidiabetic medication, is not known to cause gynaecomastia. In fact, some studies suggest it may have a protective effect against certain hormone-sensitive conditions due to its mild anti-androgenic properties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen evaluating gynaecomastia, especially in older men with multiple comorbidities, it\u0027s crucial to consider medication side effects alongside other potential causes such as hormonal imbalances, liver disease, or rarely, male breast cancer. In this case, the temporal relationship between spironolactone use and the development of gynaecomastia, along with the known side effect profile of the drug, makes it the most likely culprit among the listed medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spironolactone is a common cause of drug-induced gynaecomastia, particularly in older men.","Gynaecomastia can be a side effect of medications that affect hormone balance or have estrogenic effects.","When evaluating gynaecomastia, it\u0027s important to consider medication side effects alongside other potential causes."],"references":["Rose LI, Underwood RH, Newmark SR, Kisch ES, Williams GH. Pathophysiology of spironolactone-induced gynecomastia. Annals of internal medicine. 1977 Oct 1;87(4):398-403."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34499"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13814"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20760"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20760"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dLUl6FDC70ctwE8kxko1FuuPJcgCdR.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dLUl6FDC70ctwE8kxko1FuuPJcgCdR.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34499"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-26T21:33:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-26T21:33:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6431"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49284"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.